Date: 2025-06-14Variables do something really simple - store data. Think of variables as a box with a label - instead of having to write out all the pages of Hamlet you instead can just call it "Hamlet" every time you want to reference it. You can also change out what you put in the box - as time passes, people get different translations and interpretations and you can update the box with the newest version.
There are 8 primitive types of variables in Java, that cannot be null:Making a variable is easy - you first write the data type, then the variable name, and the = sign assigns a value to the variable.
Variables can be of MORE data types than just the primitives, though! For example, arrays, sequences/lists of numbers, are not a primitive data type. int NUMBER=50;
char CHARACTER='A';
Whenever you use a variable within code, the code will store a value in memory for it, and whenever you need to access it the code will access that section of memory directly.
This means that variables can change throughout a program- you can have a variable, like the time in a match, to affect when a climb should deploy, for example. Technical discussion
When a program gets loaded, the calculations and variables are stored in RAM (random access memory). This is not unlimited: in FRC, you have around 512 MB of RAM on the Roborio, and if you don't optimize correctly, you could have issue with the command scheduler and input lag.
Some variables are constant, which means that they won't change. However, due to the fact that it would waste a lot of memory trying to keep a variable in RAM, these are replaced at compile time.
This means that if a variable is remaining the same, you should ALWAYS use make it a constant, in order to save memory and prevent command loop overruns.
Loops come in two forms: while loops and for loops, which continuously run the same thing over and over again
You won't have to deal with them too much, but it's an important concept to know.
For loops run over and over again, and here is the syntax:for (int i=0;i&lt;100;i++) {
do stuff here 100x
}
The code above runs the code over and over again, increasing the variable until it reaches 100. You can also use the variable within the loop, which is typically the use of for loops.for (int i=0;i&lt;100;i++) {
System.out.println(i);
}
While loops only require a condition and will continue running a loop until the condition is metwhile (Motor.voltage()&lt;10) {
do something
}
A special case of while loops is when you have a condition that always becomes true, it will run forever. Make sure you always have an exit condition unless you want this to be the case!while(1==1) {}; while(true) {};
One of the most important concepts to understand is logic, which is how you control the flow of your program.
The main way to do this is with an if statement and a condition:if (a&gt;b) {
do thing 1
}
//You can also use an if/else statement!
if (a&gt;b) {
do thing 1
} else {
do thing 2
}
boolean c=true;
if (c) {
do thing 3 (will run since c==true);
} A condition is a statement that evaluates into a boolean (so you can pass a boolean in as well). You can use the == sign, &gt; or &lt; signs to create a condition. To combine conditions, you can use ! to negate a statement, || to make an or statement, and &amp;&amp; to make an and statement. If statements respect () as well, so you can make very complex if statements.

