Date: 2025-06-14A function in programming is extremely similar to a function in mathematics: you pass in some values, do something with these values, and return the modified value. The critical difference is that in programming, a function isn't restricted to modifying values, it can run anything.
An analogy would be like walking: you don't think about doing "right knee rotate left knee rotate" and every individual step, you just think about the function walking.
You create a function using the [return type][function name](). return types are explained later, for now we'll use void.Some pseudocode examples might help:void drive() {
leftMotors.spin(forward);
rightMotors.spin(forward);
}
void reverse() {
leftMotors.spin(reverse);
rightMotors.spin(reverse);
} drive();
reverse();
drive();
reverse(); //instead of
leftMotors.spin(forward);
rightMotors.spin(forward);
leftMotors.spin(reverse);
rightMotors.spin(reverse);
leftMotors.spin(forward);
rightMotors.spin(forward);
leftMotors.spin(reverse);
rightMotors.spin(reverse); A parameter is a "placeholder" value in a function. Think of it again as a mathematical function like , where you can pass in any value. is not a real value, but it is replaced when you call something like .
You place the placeholder in the () of the function. The syntax is the same as an int.
By passing in a parameter, you replace the value of the parametervoid addOne(int number) {
number++;
} Now, looking a the code, you may notice two errors: first, the function is never called (which is actually a really stupid common mistake). The second is that addOne will never do anything: sure, you'll pass in a number, like so:int number=5;
addOne(number);
//What happens now??
but the variable number will not be changed. Think about why this is the case!
In order to change it, we should use a return type and assign the variable to the function's return value.
In the code snippet, number will become 6 since addOne will return number after it increments it by 1:int addOne(int number) {
number++;
return number;
}
int N=5;
N=addOne(N);

