Date: 2025-06-14Now we get into actually important things...A class is a "type": for example, you have the "type" or "class" of Humans. Now there are many individual humans, like Jared, Zach, Mr. Patel...
However, all of these people have things that they can all do: walk, eat, think, etc.<br>
The class contains all of these as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Basic Programming II - Functions" data-href="Basic Programming II - Functions" href="to-code-a-robot/programming-basics/basic-programming-ii-functions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">functions</a>, which are called methods of the class. Whenever an Object of the class is created, the object inherits all of the same methods from the class.
Classes can also inherit from other classes, but you don't need to know that...
An example of a class is here: public class Human { public Human(String name) { } public void walk() { } public void think() { } public void eat() { }
} The WPIlib libraries and many vendor libraries run off of classes and object-oriented programming, so these concepts will be used over and over again.The constructor is a specific type of method in a class - it runs whenever you create a new object.
You create it by using public [className](), in our case it's public Human(). Like any function, you can pass parameters in here as well, so you could have public Human(String name) as an example.Creating an object of a class is simple - similar to creating a variable, but you need to use "new". Human Jared=new Human();
Human() is the constructor, so any parameters you originally created must be passed in here.
As an example, let's say you had public Human(String name) as the constructor, the example would be modified to:Human Jared=new Human("Jared");
To call a method from an object is really easy, you just do [class name].[method name](). Human Jared=new Human("Jared");
Jared.walk();
You'll use this a lot when calling motor functions.Classes can inherit from other classes - this makes a lot of sense when there's a very general class and you can make specific subclasses. For example, all subsystems can be extremely different, but they all have similar core functionality - they have commands and thus need to be able to process these commands. So every subsystem you make will extend from subsystem base.public class Elevator extends SubsystemBase { }
public class Climb extends SubsystemBase { }
