Date: 2025-06-14You may have remembered we use public when creating a class and methods, but why is that?
It's because we want these code blocks to be accessible everywhere - in the main block of the code, you should be able to use the code and run it. However, if only the class itself needs to access the code block, you should use private to represent the code block. For example, in an elevator subsystem, the main "runner" doesn't need to access the motors.public class Elevator extends SubsystemBase {
private Motor MOTOR=new Motor();
}
Unless you use the variable, object, or method somewhere else, always use private to lessen code clutter.
public and private (and all other modifiers) can be used whenever you create something - so functions, variables, objects, etc.Static is a little more confusing - it basically causes that variable to be shared among all objects.
For example:public class Human {
public static int Total_Humans=0;
public Human() {
Total_Humans=Total_Humans+1; //yes I know I can use ++
}
...class stuff here
}
public Human Jared = new Human();
public Human Zach = new Human();
Total Humans would be 2 for everybody!
This is used a lot in constants, to ensure that all subsystems share the same constants (e.g public static final int POINTS=50;)
Otherwise, it's not used that much.Final prevents the value from being changed, such as being incremented or reassigned. Always use it if possible, it's slightly more efficient and also helps protect against accidental changes to constants.
